docs.abstract: A new kind of suburbanization is sweeping through politics, from Richmond to Atlanta, Houston, Denver and elsewhere, and Democrats are starting to breach Republicans’ firewalls in elections.
docs.snippet: A new kind of suburbanization is sweeping through politics, from Richmond to Atlanta, Houston, Denver and elsewhere, and Democrats are starting to breach Republicans’ firewalls in elections.
docs.lead_paragraph: SOUTH RIDING, Va. — Not long ago, this rolling green stretch of Northern Virginia was farmland. Most people who could vote had grown up here. And when they did, they usually chose Republicans.

headline.main: How Voters Turned Virginia From Deep Red to Solid Blue
headline.print_headline: Once Red Redoubts, Suburbs Turn Virginia Blue

byline.original: By Sabrina Tavernise, Robert Gebeloff and Lauren Leatherby

docs.abstract: Mr. Sanford, a former congressman and governor of South Carolina, ended his presidential campaign just two months after it began.
docs.snippet: Mr. Sanford, a former congressman and governor of South Carolina, ended his presidential campaign just two months after it began.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Former Gov. Mark Sanford of South Carolina said on Tuesday that he was ending his long-shot primary challenge to President Trump just two months after announcing it, arguing that the impeachment inquiry had made it impossible for his message of fiscal conservatism to break through.

headline.main: Mark Sanford Drops Trump Primary Challenge: ‘You’ve Got to Be a Realist’
headline.print_headline: Sanford Drops G.O.P. ’20 Bid, Citing Inquiry As Distraction

docs.abstract: President Trump is in Louisiana two days before the election hoping to break open a deadlocked race between the Democratic incumbent and the Republican nominee.
docs.snippet: President Trump is in Louisiana two days before the election hoping to break open a deadlocked race between the Democratic incumbent and the Republican nominee.
docs.lead_paragraph: BOSSIER CITY, La. — President Trump urged Louisiana voters on Thursday to “send a message to the corrupt Democrats in Washington” by electing to governor the Republican nominee, Eddie Rispone, directly linking the impeachment inquiry to a state election that will test his clout in the Deep South.

headline.main: Two Days Before Louisiana Governor’s Race, Trump Pleads for Win
headline.print_headline: Trump Pleads for Louisiana To Deliver Him ‘a Big Win’

docs.abstract: His success, especially in Iowa, has grated on rival campaigns that say his record in government is not commensurate with the attention he’s receiving.

docs.lead_paragraph: WAVERLY, Iowa — Joseph R. Biden Jr. was mingling with a handful of mayors backstage at a conference in Washington when an uninvited guest appeared.

headline.main: Why Pete Buttigieg Annoys His Democratic Rivals
headline.print_headline: As Buttigieg Surges Ahead, Surly Looks Multiply

byline.original: By Reid J. Epstein and Lisa Lerer

docs.abstract: As Democratic presidential candidates gather to debate on Wednesday night, Barack Obama is increasingly pressing a 2020 message: Focus on defeating President Trump and ditch the ideological purity.
docs.snippet: As Democratic presidential candidates gather to debate on Wednesday night, Barack Obama is increasingly pressing a 2020 message: Focus on defeating President Trump and ditch the ideological purity.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Barack Obama had a plan of sorts for the 2020 presidential primaries, according to several allies and advisers: Stay out of the way, offer advice when asked, promote voting rights, finish a new memoir — then jump back into politics after Democrats picked their nominee.

headline.main: Obama Moves Off Political Sidelines, Earlier Than He Expected
headline.print_headline: Stepping Off the Sidelines of the Race, ‘as a Ref, Not a Player’

docs.abstract: The Kentucky governor’s race has turned into a kind of testing ground to see how transgender issues could rally support for President Trump.
docs.snippet: The Kentucky governor’s race has turned into a kind of testing ground to see how transgender issues could rally support for President Trump.
docs.lead_paragraph: ARLINGTON, Va. — From the 12th floor of a glass office tower in the Washington suburbs, a campaign to sway the governor’s race in Kentucky on Tuesday is being waged with an alarmist claim that has little to do with the race itself: If Democrats have their way, soon boys will be able to compete against girls in school sports.

headline.main: A Conservative Push to Make Trans Kids and School Sports the Next Battleground in the Culture War
headline.print_headline: Playing Field Becomes a New Battlefield Over Transgender Rights

docs.abstract: The mayor of Charleston, W.Va., wanted her city to be more welcoming to all faiths and people, so she changed an annual celebration to the ‘Winter Parade.’ It didn’t last long.

docs.lead_paragraph: CHARLESTON, W.Va. — The first shot was fired in the middle of the afternoon in early October, back when the Appalachian leaves had barely turned orange and store shelves were lined with Halloween candy.

headline.print_headline: In West Virginia, a 3-Day War Over Christmas

docs.abstract: The California senator announced her presidential campaign here with a rally for tens of thousands. Her fans loved her debate performance. But some people wonder, “Where have you been?”
docs.snippet: The California senator announced her presidential campaign here with a rally for tens of thousands. Her fans loved her debate performance. But some people wonder, “Where have you been?”
docs.lead_paragraph: OAKLAND, Calif. — When Senator Kamala Harris announced her presidential campaign on the steps of City Hall here in January, tens of thousands of people showed up, optimistically cheering for a person they believed could be the first woman — the first black woman — in the White House.

headline.main: What Does Oakland Think of Kamala Harris Now?

docs.abstract: In events across Atlanta, Ms. Warren, Bernie Sanders and others described how they would address the concerns and priorities of black voters.
docs.snippet: In events across Atlanta, Ms. Warren, Bernie Sanders and others described how they would address the concerns and priorities of black voters.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — One day after a televised debate featuring significant exchanges about race, Democratic presidential candidates fanned out across this capital of black political power to pitch their message to black voters and send a clear signal: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. should not take support from African-Americans for granted.

headline.main: Elizabeth Warren Makes Pitch to Black Women In Speech About Racial Inequities
headline.print_headline: Taking Debate Theme Outside Arena in a Bid To Earn Black Support

byline.original: By Astead W. Herndon and Thomas Kaplan

docs.abstract: At Wednesday’s debate, the California senator said politicians tend to overlook “the backbone of the Democratic Party.”
docs.snippet: At Wednesday’s debate, the California senator said politicians tend to overlook “the backbone of the Democratic Party.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Kamala Harris of California criticized some of her opponents at the debate on Wednesday night for their attitudes toward black women, saying they praised black women for consistently supporting Democratic candidates but took their votes for granted.

headline.main: Watch Kamala Harris Criticize Politicians for Taking Black Women for Granted
